name: Greenback Dollar
comments: The Weems Family was an instrumental string band. However, in December 1927, at their only recording session, they were told that they needed lyrics for the songs to be recorded. One of these was ''Callahan's Reel." Consequently, they created a minimal set of lyrics: Over the hill and down the holler All I want is a greenback dollar (2) Over the hill and down the holler All I want is a sweet little mama. Their recording now had a few lyrics but it was primarily an instrumental. The "Callahan's Reel" tune and the Weem's Family lyrics were employed by The New Lost City Ramblers for their version of "Greenback Dollar."

name: The Tree on the Hill
comments: A simple cumulative song in which a sequence of natural elements are linked, generally by diminishing scale (wood/hill/bog> tree> branch> twig> nest> bird> egg/feather, etc) but also sometimes as a “circle of life” (feather, bed, lass, lad, babe).  It is popular as a children’s song and known by many titles.  The Tree on the Hill is the earliest known title from the chapbook “Two Excellent New Songs”, printed in London in the 1790s.  The Bog in the Valley/Rattlin' Bog appears to be associated mostly with Scottish/Irish versions.  Similar songs exist in Welsh, Breton, Danish, French, Dutch but the earliest origins are not certain.  The song is collected as #129 in the Roud Index of Folk Songs as The Tree in the Wood.

name: Hallelujah, I'm a Bum
comments: Although his credit for this work is described as a "questionable theory" by some, McClintock claimed to have written the original lyrics to this song in 1897 or 1898, putting them to the tune of "Revive Us Again".  McClintock is known to have sung the song no later than early 1898.  What seems to make McClintock's authorship "questionable" to many is that he would have only been 15 years old when the song was written.  McClintock, however, had run away from home at age 14, and hoboed to New Orleans where he had his first experiences with the type of men that are the subject of this song.  While age 15 is young for a songwriter, it is by no means outlandishly young. Bud L. McKillips, who was a journalist for labor publications,  contends that the words were written by an unknown member of the International Workers of the World ("IWW").  From its inception in1905, McClintock had himself been a dedicated Wobbly.  During demonstrations in Spokane, Washington in 1906, the Wobblies, who were often drowned out by Salvation Army Bands sent in by business managements, adopted the strategy of writing parody lyrics to the tunes sung by the Salvation Army.  McClintock was, in fact, part of the IWW songwriting team so it is far from inconceivable that he is the Wobbly who wrote this song. Others credit a Kansas City hobo, "One Finger Ellis" for writing some or all of the verses to "Hallelujah, I'm a Bum" while in jail.  It is certainly possible that such an individual wrote additional verses to the song as it was a common occurrence for new verses to be written for true folksongs. Although not truly a folksong, it is collected as number 7992 in the Roud Folk Song Index.

name: Dark Hollow
comments: In 1958, the little-known West Virginian Bill Browning released his rockabilly country song "Dark Hollow" as a b-side to "Borned with the Blues".  Luke Gordon and Jimmie Skinner quickly covered the song in a more Hank Williams-style set more closely to the tune of the traditional Appalachian song East Virginia . Their versions had much wider distribution and have been covered by countless others, including The Grateful Dead.  Many of the bluegrass versions of "Dark Hollow" incorporate some of the verses from the "East Virginia" family of songs and are harder to classify.  Browning's original song had very simple lyrics - he essentially copied the first verse of lyrics from Buell Kazee's 1927 "East Virginia" and Clarence Ashley's 1929 song "Dark Holler Blues" (which itself was a derivative of "East Virginia") that said "I'd rather be in some dark holler where the sun don't ever shine....".  Because of the similarities to the "East Virginia" family of songs SHS is setting this up as an adaptation.  Browning's "Dark Hollow" lyrics: I'd rather be in some dark hollow, Where the sun don't never shine, Than to be at home alone just knowing that she's gone, That would cause me to lose my mind CHO: So pray train blows your whistle, Take me far on down the track I'm going away, I'm leaving today, I'm going but I ain't coming back

comments: Fiddle tune widely known throughout southeastern United States. Researchers have found several possible origins of this tune based on the lives of real Joe Clarks in Virginia, Kentucky & Maryland. Old Joe Clark may even have started out as a ballad which then later became a popular fiddle tune, instead of the lyrics being added to an already existing fiddle tune. Others suggest it first circulated in children's tradition and in play-parties and later was introduced into the fiddle and banjo world.
